#!/usr/bin/env bash
# warren — daily digest (Type B1: cron → bus → orchestrator wakes up → Telegram).
# Does NOT use `claude -p`. Writes one bus message; the bus daemon pushes it to the
# already-running orchestrator. Cron example: 0 7 * * *
#
# Fill {{WARREN_ROOT}} and {{ORCH_LC}} when you install this (bootstrap can do it).
export PATH="/opt/homebrew/bin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin:/usr/sbin:/sbin:$PATH"

WARREN_ROOT="{{WARREN_ROOT}}"
ORCH="{{ORCH_LC}}"
BODY_FILE="$(mktemp /tmp/warren_digest.XXXXXX)"

cat > "$BODY_FILE" <<'BODY'
Produce the daily digest. Read files NOW — don't trust cached session state.
For each domain agent:
  1. grep '^## \[' <Domain>/log.md | tail -3        (recent ops)
  2. find <Domain>/wiki/ -name "*.md" | sort | tail -1   (newest content file)
Use the LATER of the two dates as "last activity".
Build a one-line-per-agent brief: "Name: what happened / last file YYYY-MM-DD".
Add "⚠️ Attention: ..." for anything overdue or stuck.
Send the final text to Telegram (creds in config/credentials/telegram-bot.md, via curl).
If a domain has no log entry AND no new wiki file in > 10 days, send it a bus message:
  <repo>/core/bus/send.sh --to <agent> --from <orch> --title "digest-alert" --body "<what>"
Do all of this autonomously — no questions.
BODY

"$WARREN_ROOT/core/bus/send.sh" --to "$ORCH" --from cron --title "daily-digest" --body-file "$BODY_FILE"
rm -f "$BODY_FILE"
